sture changes, presenting a new resource base for spatial changes to species composition and growth rates.{\textless}P{\textgreater} The major hydroecological responses to elevated CO$_{\textrm{2}}$ are seen as increased maximum upper canopy leaf area, increased litter inputs, especially at times of drought (hence changed fire regimes), changes in the composition of the understorey (hence litter composition, soil microfauna, and the spatial expression of biological diversity) and a slight increase in water yield.},
